{"problem_text": "A compound contains by mass 40.92 \% potassium, 12.00 \% carbon, and 47.08 \% oxygen. Calculate the empirical formula of the compound.", "answer_latex": "K_2CO_3", "answer_number": "", "unit": "", "source":"GPT-4", "problemid":"1.1_26", "comment": " ", "solution": "To find the empirical formula, first calculate the moles of each element. Assume you have 100 g of the compound, which would contain 40.92 g potassium, 12.00 g carbon, and 47.08 g oxygen:
$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathrm{moles\; of\; potassium} & =\frac{40.92 ~ \mathrm{g}}{39.10 ~ \mathrm{g/mol}} = 1.047 ~ \mathrm{mol} \\
\mathrm{moles\; of\; carbon} & =\frac{12.00 ~ \mathrm{g}}{12.01 ~ \mathrm{g/mol}} = 1.000 ~ \mathrm{mol} \\
\mathrm{moles\; of\; oxygen} & =\frac{47.08 ~ \mathrm{g}}{16.00 ~ \mathrm{g/mol}} = 2.943 ~ \mathrm{mol}
\end{aligned}
$$
Divide all mole values by the smallest mole value (1.000 for carbon) to obtain the mole ratio:
$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathrm{potassium:carbon:oxygen} &= \frac{1.047}{1.000} : \frac{1.000}{1.000} : \frac{2.943}{1.000} \\
& \approx 1:1:3
\end{aligned}
$$
The empirical formula for the compound is K$_2$CO$_3$."}

