{"problem_text": "A $5.00\mathrm{~g}$ sample of carbon dioxide, $\mathrm{CO_2}$, is heated at constant pressure until its internal energy doubles. How much heat, $q$, is absorbed in joules?", "answer_latex": " 1.07", "answer_number": "1.07", "unit": "$10^4\mathrm{~J}$", "source": "GPT-4", "problemid": "1.1_3", "comment": " ", "solution": "First we need to find the moles of CO2 in the 5.00 g sample. The molar mass of CO2 is $12.01 \mathrm{~g/mol} (\textrm{C}) + 2( 16.00\mathrm{~g/mol}  (\mathrm{O}))= 44.01 \mathrm{~g/mol}$. So,
$$
\begin{aligned}
n=\frac{5.00\mathrm{~g}}{44.01 \mathrm{~g/mol}} &= 0.1135 \mathrm{~mol}
\end{aligned}
$$
For CO2, the molar heat capacity at constant pressure ($C_p$) is $37.11\mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol} \cdot \mathrm{K}$. The internal energy is directly proportional to its absolute temperature, $U \propto T$. If $U$ doubles, so does $T$. Hence, $\Delta T$ equals the initial temperature $T$. The amount of heat ($q$) absorbed will be:
$$
\begin{aligned}
q=nC_p \Delta T &= (0.1135 \mathrm{~mol})(37.11 \mathrm{~J/mol} \cdot \mathrm{K})(T)\\
&= T(4.219 \mathrm{~J/K})
\end{aligned}
$$
Since $\Delta T = T$, we can write:
$$
q= T^2(4.219 \mathrm{~J/K})
$$
Knowing that $T$ doubles, we can write:
$$
q= 2T^2(4.219 \mathrm{~J/K})= 1.07 \times 10^4 \mathrm{~J}
$$"}

