$$
E_{\mathrm{N_2}} = 5 \times \frac{1}{2}k_BT
$$
Substitute the Boltzmann constant ($k_B = 1.381 \times 10^{-23} \mathrm{~J/K}$) and the given temperature (300 K).
$$
E_{\mathrm{N_2}} = 5 \times \frac{1}{2}(1.381 \times 10^{-23} \mathrm{~J/K})(300 \mathrm{K}) = 2.071 \times 10^{-21} \mathrm{~J} 
$$
To find the energy per mole, multiply the energy per molecule by Avogadro's number (6.022 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}).
$$
E_{\mathrm{N_2}} = (2.071 \times 10^{-21} \mathrm{~J})\times (6.022 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}) = 12.467 \times 10^2 \mathrm{~J/mol}
$$
Convert the energy to kJ/mol.
$$
E_{\mathrm{N_2}} = 12.467 \times 10^2 \mathrm{~J/mol} \times \frac{1 \mathrm{~kJ}}{1000 \mathrm{~J}} = 6.07 \mathrm{~kJ/mol} $$"}

